WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

2
00:00:59.624 --> 00:01:01.182
Kaylie!

3
00:01:01.183 --> 00:01:02.892
Shh!

4
00:01:22.042 --> 00:01:23.830
And I fired.

5
00:01:25.519 --> 00:01:27.944
As many times as I've
had this dream...

6
00:01:28.636 --> 00:01:30.379
it's never been me before.

7
00:01:31.073 --> 00:01:32.578
Holding the gun.

8
00:01:32.911 --> 00:01:34.541
I know.

9
00:01:36.148 --> 00:01:37.971
That's very good.

10
00:01:39.625 --> 00:01:44.419
It implies a true. deeply-rooted
acceptance of responsibility.

11
00:01:44.420 --> 00:01:46.857
And it tells me that you haven't
only overcome your delusion

12
00:01:46.858 --> 00:01:48.375
in your conscious mind...

13
00:01:48.376 --> 00:01:50.893
but in his subconscious
mind as well.

14
00:01:50.894 --> 00:01:53.650
It's my opinion that
Tim is a healthy adult

15
00:01:53.651 --> 00:01:56.847
who represents no danger
to himself or anyone else.

16
00:01:56.848 --> 00:02:00.603
And I believe he should be
discharged. as the state requested.

17
00:02:00.604 --> 00:02:03.030
on his upcoming 21st birthday.

18
00:02:09.875 --> 00:02:12.232
going once...

19
00:02:12.233 --> 00:02:14.549
11-5 twice...

20
00:02:14.550 --> 00:02:16.108
Sold to the gentleman.

21
00:02:16.109 --> 00:02:20.126
Congratulations to you. sir.
That's bidder number 131.

22
00:02:22.622 --> 00:02:24.899
All right. and our
next item for bid

23
00:02:24.900 --> 00:02:29.654
is a gorgeous antique mirror.
recovered from the Levesque Estate.

24
00:02:29.655 --> 00:02:32.572
The Lasser Glass is a
well-traveled gem.

25
00:02:32.573 --> 00:02:36.128
It spent several seasons adorning
the walls at Balmoral Castle.

26
00:02:36.129 --> 00:02:38.366
Scottish home of the Royal Family.

27
00:02:38.367 --> 00:02:41.763
This is the original glass
and the original frame.

28
00:02:41.764 --> 00:02:45.239
The mirror is in remarkable condition.
save for a small hairline fracture

29
00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:47.157
down in the lower
right-hand corner.

30
00:02:47.158 --> 00:02:51.033
The frame is carved out of one
piece of Bavarian Black Cedar.

31
00:02:51.034 --> 00:02:52.792
And we will go ahead
and start the bidding

32
00:02:52.793 --> 00:02:55.069
at a conservative
10.000 dollars.

33
00:02:55.070 --> 00:02:57.307
Do I have 10? Right here
in front. Thank you. sir.

34
00:02:57.308 --> 00:02:59.185
Your sister is
picking you up. then?

35
00:02:59.186 --> 00:03:02.885
Her message even said something
about helping me find a job.

36
00:03:03.542 --> 00:03:05.699
That'd be wonderful
for your transition.

37
00:03:05.700 --> 00:03:07.537
We're at 12.000
dollars on the phone...

38
00:03:07.538 --> 00:03:09.735
You sure you don't want
me to come with you?

39
00:03:09.736 --> 00:03:13.611
- Some moral support?
- No. But thank you.

40
00:03:13.612 --> 00:03:16.169
I think I better do
this part myself.

41
00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:18.966
- Wait up for us.
- Of course.

42
00:03:18.967 --> 00:03:21.803
Remember what we talked about.

43
00:03:21.804 --> 00:03:24.401
You've had a support system.
a mandated support system.

44
00:03:24.402 --> 00:03:27.997
to help you get well. Kaylie
had to get by on her own.

45
00:03:27.998 --> 00:03:31.713
It's very important that you
reconnect with your sister.

46
00:03:31.714 --> 00:03:35.810
But it's more important that
you protect your recovery.

47
00:03:38.508 --> 00:03:40.944
- 16.000.
- 16.000 on Skype.

48
00:03:40.945 --> 00:03:44.701
That is 16. going once.
16 twice.

49
00:03:44.702 --> 00:03:46.978
Sold. Please pass along
our congratulations.

50
00:03:46.979 --> 00:03:48.961
- See you tonight.
- OK.

51
00:04:01.165 --> 00:04:04.511
Son. just pull the
door when it buzzes.

52
00:04:26.940 --> 00:04:28.967
Hey. little brother.

53
00:04:40.207 --> 00:04:42.632
Your half of the estate.

54
00:04:44.842 --> 00:04:46.719
Oh. apartments.

55
00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:48.558
So all the studies say
that you should transition

56
00:04:48.559 --> 00:04:50.356
to a place that isn't
necessarily large.

57
00:04:50.357 --> 00:04:52.434
so I printed off some
listings for studios.

58
00:04:52.435 --> 00:04:55.950
But in the meantime. until
you find one you like.

59
00:04:55.951 --> 00:04:58.172
we would love it if
you stayed with us.

60
00:04:59.708 --> 00:05:01.545
Kaylie. I don't know
how to thank you.

61
00:05:01.546 --> 00:05:04.926
Well. I wanted to talk to you
about all of this sooner.

62
00:05:06.421 --> 00:05:08.960
But suddenly they wouldn't
let me in to see you.

63
00:05:10.577 --> 00:05:12.974
It wasn't...

64
00:05:12.975 --> 00:05:16.559
It wasn't that they wouldn't
let you in to see me.

65
00:05:18.209 --> 00:05:22.305
I just had some things I needed
to figure out for myself.

66
00:05:26.801 --> 00:05:28.464
I get it.

67
00:05:29.358 --> 00:05:31.555
I'm your family.

68
00:05:31.556 --> 00:05:34.425
The only thing that matters
is that you're here now.

69
00:05:42.546 --> 00:05:44.289
I found it.

70
00:05:49.978 --> 00:05:52.974
- What do you mean?
- You know.

71
00:05:52.975 --> 00:05:54.733
It wasn't easy.

72
00:05:54.734 --> 00:05:56.571
I tracked it down mostly
through second bidders.

73
00:05:56.572 --> 00:05:58.369
people who lost at the auctions.

74
00:05:58.370 --> 00:06:00.886
It was in storage. part of an
estate collection in Bremen.

75
00:06:00.887 --> 00:06:03.564
It took me a year and a half
to get it into our warehouse

76
00:06:03.565 --> 00:06:05.242
and it lasted less than a week.

77
00:06:05.243 --> 00:06:08.159
It's about to ship out to a new
buyer. so we only have a few days.

78
00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:10.108
but it should be enough.

79
00:06:11.437 --> 00:06:13.897
A few days for what. Kaylie?

80
00:06:14.954 --> 00:06:17.458
To keep our promise.

81
00:06:18.790 --> 00:06:20.533
And kill it.

82
00:06:30.938 --> 00:06:32.775
OK. guys. the couch can go there.

83
00:06:32.776 --> 00:06:34.733
And those boxes are kitchen.

84
00:06:34.734 --> 00:06:37.841
- Bam! Bam!
- Tim. we don't shoot the movers.

85
00:06:39.769 --> 00:06:42.525
And as soon as I get my files
organized. you will have them.

86
00:06:42.526 --> 00:06:44.124
Yes. Shoot.

87
00:06:44.125 --> 00:06:45.709
Can I call you back?

88
00:06:47.641 --> 00:06:50.358
Jeff. I am so sorry I
didn't return your call.

89
00:06:50.359 --> 00:06:53.874
I've just been slammed. It's a lot
easier when you have a staff.

90
00:06:53.875 --> 00:06:57.631
- Kaylie's under arrest.
- She's not here. buddy.

91
00:06:57.632 --> 00:06:58.989
Sneak attack!

92
00:06:58.990 --> 00:07:00.867
You are so dead!

93
00:07:00.868 --> 00:07:02.466
Honey?

94
00:07:02.467 --> 00:07:05.783
And this goes? OK.
against the wall.

95
00:07:05.784 --> 00:07:07.541
Watch the molding.

96
00:07:07.542 --> 00:07:11.657
Thank you. OK. OK. It's fragile.

97
00:07:13.136 --> 00:07:15.493
- Hey. guys! Take it outside.
- But. Mom...

98
00:07:15.494 --> 00:07:17.411
The alternative is moving boxes.

99
00:07:17.412 --> 00:07:18.770
Oh. come on. Come on.

100
00:07:18.771 --> 00:07:20.648
So we'll talk soon. OK.

101
00:07:20.649 --> 00:07:22.806
Thanks. guys. OK.

102
00:07:22.807 --> 00:07:25.323
I'll be right out.

103
00:07:25.324 --> 00:07:27.361
So you expanded the
furniture order?

104
00:07:27.362 --> 00:07:30.438
I don't know if I'm
loving this desk here.

105
00:07:30.439 --> 00:07:34.104
Were you gonna tell me or just
wait till I saw the Visa bill?

106
00:07:35.275 --> 00:07:36.574
Hold on.

107
00:07:38.312 --> 00:07:43.545
I was hoping to smooth that over
with a 3-piece vanity set

108
00:07:43.546 --> 00:07:47.382
that is supposed to be here...
Is it not here?

109
00:07:50.460 --> 00:07:53.256
I get it. OK. Do your
office however you want.

110
00:07:53.257 --> 00:07:54.934
- Thank you.
- Mm-hm.

111
00:07:54.935 --> 00:07:58.131
It's a bit ostentatious.
though. don't you think?

112
00:07:58.132 --> 00:08:01.648
I'm confused. because you
wanted the antiques.

113
00:08:01.649 --> 00:08:03.566
And I said I was fine with IKEA.

114
00:08:03.567 --> 00:08:06.283
Yeah. I wanted to get a few
pieces to upgrade the place.

115
00:08:06.284 --> 00:08:07.961
not turn it into a showroom.

116
00:08:07.962 --> 00:08:11.238
Listen. we got a new
home. a new company.

117
00:08:11.239 --> 00:08:14.540
so we get new furniture.
Makes sense.

118
00:08:15.235 --> 00:08:17.432
Same old wife. though. right?

119
00:08:17.433 --> 00:08:20.336
Well. I told you I
was fine with IKEA.

120
00:08:21.309 --> 00:08:24.337
- Kidding.
- I'm not IKEA.

121
00:08:31.379 --> 00:08:34.975
You sure you prefer this?

122
00:08:34.976 --> 00:08:38.515
Our guest room is a
lot nicer than this.

123
00:08:39.411 --> 00:08:42.315
Yeah. I think it might be best.

124
00:08:43.008 --> 00:08:44.432
My own space.

125
00:08:51.599 --> 00:08:54.706
You promised me you'd never
forget what really happened.

126
00:08:55.715 --> 00:08:57.504
You promised.

127
00:08:58.553 --> 00:09:00.789
I was 10 years old.

128
00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:02.420
Well...

129
00:09:03.428 --> 00:09:05.585
I'm doing it tomorrow night.

130
00:09:05.586 --> 00:09:09.284
And... I could really.
really use your help.

131
00:09:15.736 --> 00:09:17.604
Good night. Tim.

132
00:09:44.347 --> 00:09:48.205
I feel like my scar is more noticeable
now than it was 10 years ago.

133
00:09:49.303 --> 00:09:51.459
Let me take a look.
I'm a professional.

134
00:09:52.979 --> 00:09:56.175
What scar?

135
00:09:56.176 --> 00:09:59.372
We're nowhere near done.

136
00:09:59.373 --> 00:10:00.650
So?

137
00:10:00.651 --> 00:10:03.031
You've only put together the bed.

138
00:10:03.728 --> 00:10:05.710
That wasn't easy.

139
00:10:46.926 --> 00:10:48.794
Damn it.

140
00:11:10.742 --> 00:11:12.644
Shit.

141
00:12:53.681 --> 00:12:56.557
No! No! No!

142
00:12:56.558 --> 00:13:01.153
No! No! No!

143
00:13:01.154 --> 00:13:05.269
It's OK. It's OK. It's OK.

144
00:13:05.270 --> 00:13:07.626
It's OK. It's OK.

145
00:13:07.627 --> 00:13:12.302
It's just one of your night
terrors. It's OK. Shh...

146
00:13:12.303 --> 00:13:15.603
Shh...

147
00:13:47.508 --> 00:13:48.866
- Hey.
- Hey.

148
00:13:48.867 --> 00:13:51.943
So I requisitioned you your own printer.
You don't have to share anymore.

149
00:13:51.944 --> 00:13:55.179
- We'll take you off the network.
- OK.

150
00:13:55.180 --> 00:13:57.497
Because I guess there were
some complaints about people

151
00:13:57.498 --> 00:14:00.015
printing out their sales reports
and finding some really...

152
00:14:00.016 --> 00:14:03.012
graphic crime scene
photos from. uh...

153
00:14:03.013 --> 00:14:05.120
your computer.

154
00:14:12.403 --> 00:14:15.280
I noticed you put in a transfer
order for the Lasser Glass.

155
00:14:15.281 --> 00:14:17.797
- Yeah. as a repair.
- Oh.

156
00:14:17.798 --> 00:14:19.715
I thought Warren said no repairs.

157
00:14:19.716 --> 00:14:21.698
He changed his mind.

158
00:14:22.833 --> 00:14:25.150
Got to be honest. I'm really
just waiting for an explanation

159
00:14:25.151 --> 00:14:27.497
for the corpse print-outs.

160
00:14:38.218 --> 00:14:40.894
I know things have
been strange at times.

161
00:14:40.895 --> 00:14:42.972
And you know I'm dealing
with some dark stuff.

162
00:14:42.973 --> 00:14:45.672
some parental stuff. with Tim out.

163
00:14:49.407 --> 00:14:52.435
I'll never expect you to
understand that part of my life.

164
00:14:53.323 --> 00:14:55.840
Just bear with me a
day or two more.

165
00:14:55.841 --> 00:14:58.397
Things will get back to normal.

166
00:14:58.398 --> 00:15:00.062
I promise.

167
00:15:08.149 --> 00:15:11.624
I don't usually get transfer orders
to third-party repair houses.

168
00:15:11.625 --> 00:15:14.981
Oh. yeah. the buyer wants his guy
to look at it before it ships.

169
00:15:14.982 --> 00:15:17.458
- But we both know you'd do it better.
- No argument there.

170
00:15:17.459 --> 00:15:20.885
I'll take it there myself. Babysit
it every step of the way.

171
00:15:22.814 --> 00:15:25.717
Better get some furni pads
if we're going to move her.

172
00:15:50.587 --> 00:15:52.649
Hello again.

173
00:16:02.935 --> 00:16:04.997
You must be hungry.

174
00:16:16.321 --> 00:16:18.906
I hope this still hurts.

175
00:17:43.156 --> 00:17:44.819
You're all set.

176
00:17:45.514 --> 00:17:47.143
You all right?

177
00:17:50.868 --> 00:17:52.214
I'm great.

178
00:17:55.224 --> 00:17:57.221
The guys will wrap her
up for you in a bit.

179
00:17:57.222 --> 00:17:58.965
Thank you. Warren.

180
00:18:12.327 --> 00:18:14.684
I'll see you at home.

181
00:18:14.685 --> 00:18:17.826
My car is by the loading dock.

182
00:18:19.161 --> 00:18:20.718
- Hello.
- Hey.

183
00:18:20.719 --> 00:18:22.756
- Got a phone.
- Cool.

184
00:18:22.757 --> 00:18:24.195
You just need to sign the order.

185
00:18:24.196 --> 00:18:26.992
I don't feel good about the
way we left it last night.

186
00:18:26.993 --> 00:18:28.790
Can we meet up somewhere and talk?

187
00:18:28.791 --> 00:18:31.268
Of course. Can you
come by the house?

188
00:18:31.269 --> 00:18:33.066
Sure. What's your address?

189
00:18:33.067 --> 00:18:36.174
No. The house.

190
00:19:13.507 --> 00:19:15.904
Yes. I have it in front of me.

191
00:19:15.905 --> 00:19:19.180
I don't know. probably half
an hour. Does that work?

192
00:19:19.181 --> 00:19:20.739
OK.

193
00:19:20.740 --> 00:19:22.608
Speak then.

194
00:20:11.170 --> 00:20:12.728
Oh. crap.

195
00:20:12.729 --> 00:20:14.806
I'm gonna get you. you little brat!

196
00:20:19.003 --> 00:20:20.440
The answer is still no.

197
00:20:20.441 --> 00:20:22.798
Oh. my God. Ally has one
and Maddie has one.

198
00:20:22.799 --> 00:20:25.116
I'm the only kid in my
class without a phone.

199
00:20:25.117 --> 00:20:26.954
That is terrible.

200
00:20:26.955 --> 00:20:29.072
Thanks for nothing. Marie.

201
00:20:29.073 --> 00:20:31.150
Oh!

202
00:20:31.151 --> 00:20:34.626
I'm going to run out and get one
for you right now. daughter.

203
00:20:34.627 --> 00:20:37.583
love of my life. fruit of my loins.

204
00:20:37.584 --> 00:20:39.805
Well. I wish I'd been a pineapple.

205
00:20:44.857 --> 00:20:47.973
Hey kids. do me a favor and don't ever
chew your nails like your father.

206
00:20:47.974 --> 00:20:50.331
- It's gross.
- Hey. Dad?

207
00:20:50.332 --> 00:20:52.249
OK... He's Dad. I'm Marie.

208
00:20:52.250 --> 00:20:55.566
Who was that lady in
your office today?

209
00:20:55.567 --> 00:20:59.992
Yeah. Dad. who was that
lady in your office today?

210
00:21:01.241 --> 00:21:02.870
What lady?

211
00:21:04.797 --> 00:21:07.462
I don't know. Just some lady.

212
00:21:11.151 --> 00:21:12.736
I don't know.

213
00:21:37.445 --> 00:21:39.522
It looks so small.

214
00:21:39.523 --> 00:21:42.160
- Go on. Dog.
- You named your dog. Dog?

215
00:21:42.161 --> 00:21:45.348
No. He doesn't have a name.

216
00:21:46.237 --> 00:21:47.775
Are you OK?

217
00:21:49.833 --> 00:21:51.735
Oh. of course.

218
00:21:53.030 --> 00:21:54.978
You haven't been here since...

219
00:21:58.784 --> 00:22:00.494
Why don't you look around?

220
00:23:07.157 --> 00:23:10.752
The house just sat on the market
while I was in the foster system.

221
00:23:10.753 --> 00:23:14.029
Released to me when I turned 18.

222
00:23:14.030 --> 00:23:17.456
I was the only homeowner in the
freshman dorms when I started school.

223
00:23:20.424 --> 00:23:23.260
I'm thinking we should
try and sell it. though.

224
00:23:23.261 --> 00:23:25.163
You know. after.

225
00:23:27.177 --> 00:23:30.125
So will you help me with
something before you go?

226
00:23:40.244 --> 00:23:42.601
How the hell did you expect to
get this thing in here yourself?

227
00:23:42.602 --> 00:23:44.239
To be honest. I didn't.

228
00:23:44.240 --> 00:23:46.397
I always thought
it'd be both of us.

229
00:23:46.398 --> 00:23:48.675
Over here for now.

230
00:23:48.676 --> 00:23:50.101
OK.

231
00:24:23.522 --> 00:24:25.479
What's that?

232
00:24:25.480 --> 00:24:27.746
Yacht anchor. Kill switch.

233
00:24:29.836 --> 00:24:31.833
So. uh...

234
00:24:31.834 --> 00:24:33.591
I understand if you
don't want to stay.

235
00:24:33.592 --> 00:24:37.256
I accept that. but I
got to get started.

236
00:24:43.342 --> 00:24:45.642
I'll stay for a little bit.

237
00:24:48.617 --> 00:24:50.280
Excuse me.

238
00:24:57.528 --> 00:25:01.883
Hello. My name
is Kaylie Ann Russell.

239
00:25:01.884 --> 00:25:03.202
I'm 23 years old.

240
00:25:03.203 --> 00:25:05.639
I'm with my brother.
Timothy Alan Russell.

241
00:25:05.640 --> 00:25:07.478
Alan. of course. after his father.

242
00:25:07.479 --> 00:25:09.142
He's...

243
00:25:10.915 --> 00:25:12.513
He's 21 years old.

244
00:25:12.514 --> 00:25:15.230
It's 4:15pm on October 13th.

245
00:25:15.231 --> 00:25:17.907
and we are at 2705 Hawthorne Way.

246
00:25:17.908 --> 00:25:22.383
I'll begin by detailing my precautions
before I place and uncover the glass.

247
00:25:22.384 --> 00:25:25.100
There are three cameras. each on
its own independent power circuit.

248
00:25:25.101 --> 00:25:27.897
so if any anomalies occur. there
can be a lucid. objective record.

249
00:25:27.898 --> 00:25:30.934
I have private land lines for today's
experiment. along with my cell phone.

250
00:25:30.935 --> 00:25:33.572
And I will now ask my
brother for his phone.

251
00:25:33.573 --> 00:25:36.952
so that I can control
all electronic devices.

252
00:25:42.844 --> 00:25:44.473
I just got this. you know.

253
00:25:45.281 --> 00:25:46.991
Thanks. Timbo.

254
00:25:48.958 --> 00:25:51.354
This alarm is set to go
off every 45 minutes

255
00:25:51.355 --> 00:25:53.592
to remind me to change the
tapes in the cameras.

256
00:25:53.593 --> 00:25:56.269
This alarm is set to go off
hourly to remind us to eat.

257
00:25:56.270 --> 00:25:59.267
And we're fully stocked on
water to prevent dehydration.

258
00:25:59.268 --> 00:26:00.945
Now. as for the house itself...

259
00:26:00.946 --> 00:26:03.502
each room is fitted with
its own thermostat.

260
00:26:03.503 --> 00:26:06.100
from which data is collected by
software designed to track and record

261
00:26:06.101 --> 00:26:07.738
temperature fluctuations
in hospitals.

262
00:26:07.739 --> 00:26:10.535
Any temperature changes greater than
five degrees in either direction

263
00:26:10.536 --> 00:26:12.613
will set off an alarm.

264
00:26:12.614 --> 00:26:14.412
A third precaution
is also in place.

265
00:26:14.413 --> 00:26:16.689
but I'll get into that
in a few more minutes.

266
00:26:16.690 --> 00:26:18.967
So...

267
00:26:18.968 --> 00:26:20.965
The purpose of today's experiment

268
00:26:20.966 --> 00:26:23.403
is to prove that the object
behind me. the Lasser Glass.

269
00:26:23.404 --> 00:26:26.759
is home to an observable.
predictable supernatural force.

270
00:26:26.760 --> 00:26:29.317
There's no scientific equivalent
for the word "haunted."

271
00:26:29.318 --> 00:26:33.153
so we'll just say this object is
responsible for at least 45 deaths

272
00:26:33.154 --> 00:26:35.471
in the 4 centuries of
its recorded existence...

273
00:26:35.472 --> 00:26:37.709
Can I just stop you for a second?

274
00:26:37.710 --> 00:26:39.930
Don't ever turn off a camera.

275
00:26:41.426 --> 00:26:43.010
Sorry.

276
00:26:49.578 --> 00:26:52.055
The origin of the Lasser
Glass is unknown.

277
00:26:52.056 --> 00:26:54.172
so I can't provide a
complete history.

278
00:26:54.173 --> 00:26:58.169
but the trail starts
in London in 1754.

279
00:26:58.170 --> 00:27:01.445
Philip Lasser. the 17th
Earl of Leicester.

280
00:27:01.446 --> 00:27:04.083
acquired the mirror and hung
it over his fireplace. and...

281
00:27:04.084 --> 00:27:06.880
Another precaution.

282
00:27:06.881 --> 00:27:09.038
Hi. sweetie. How are you?

283
00:27:09.039 --> 00:27:12.794
Well. I'm checking in.
uh. as requested.

284
00:27:12.795 --> 00:27:14.912
- You all right?
- Everything's fine.

285
00:27:14.913 --> 00:27:17.629
I know this is silly to ask. but
could you try to call on the hour?

286
00:27:17.630 --> 00:27:19.667
It's about 7 past.

287
00:27:19.668 --> 00:27:23.663
- Uh... Sure.
- I'll talk to you in 53 minutes.

288
00:27:23.664 --> 00:27:26.461
And I love you.

289
00:27:26.462 --> 00:27:29.977
I'm expecting regular calls
from my fiance. Michael Dumont.

290
00:27:29.978 --> 00:27:32.095
I told him I'm nervous to be
spending time with my recently

291
00:27:32.096 --> 00:27:33.893
un-incarcerated brother.
with instructions...

292
00:27:33.894 --> 00:27:35.212
- to notify the authorities immediately
- Wow.

293
00:27:35.213 --> 00:27:36.691
if I do not answer the phone.

294
00:27:36.692 --> 00:27:39.528
- In the room.
- Nothing personal.

295
00:27:39.529 --> 00:27:43.444
So. in 1755. Philip Lasser was
found in their grand fireplace.

296
00:27:43.445 --> 00:27:47.400
Burned beyond recognition.
While his estate was dismantled

297
00:27:47.401 --> 00:27:49.118
and scattered throughout
southern England.

298
00:27:49.119 --> 00:27:51.676
one of the family's stewards claimed
to see Philip reflected in the mirror.

299
00:27:51.677 --> 00:27:53.954
An allegation apparently taken
seriously enough to warrant

300
00:27:53.955 --> 00:27:55.992
a Church investigation
into the house.

301
00:27:55.993 --> 00:27:58.109
The glass. thereafter known
as the Lasser Glass.

302
00:27:58.110 --> 00:28:00.787
is sold in public auction in 1758.

303
00:28:00.788 --> 00:28:03.904
The next known owner is an
American rail road tycoon.

304
00:28:03.905 --> 00:28:06.421
named Robert Clancy. 1864.

305
00:28:06.422 --> 00:28:08.899
Clancy apparently weighed
over 300 pounds.

306
00:28:08.900 --> 00:28:11.177
In fact. while attending
university in Connecticut.

307
00:28:11.178 --> 00:28:12.895
he was known as the
South Windham Whale.

308
00:28:12.896 --> 00:28:15.732
He hung the glass in his
ballroom in Atlanta.

309
00:28:15.733 --> 00:28:18.250
Later that year. Robert
Clancy is photographed

310
00:28:18.251 --> 00:28:20.408
by a local newspaper and. uh...

311
00:28:20.409 --> 00:28:22.845
Well. he's dropped a few pounds.

312
00:28:22.846 --> 00:28:26.082
His obit was printed a few weeks later.
Doesn't list a cause of death.

313
00:28:26.083 --> 00:28:28.839
Unfortunately. he and his
estate and the glass

314
00:28:28.840 --> 00:28:32.556
are presumably destroyed in Sherman's
march to the ocean in 1865.

315
00:28:32.557 --> 00:28:35.353
And after that. the glass is lost.

316
00:28:35.354 --> 00:28:38.030
Until it resurfaces in
turn-of-the-century New England.

317
00:28:38.031 --> 00:28:41.707
The next case of note
is Mary O'Connor. 1904.

318
00:28:41.708 --> 00:28:43.425
She hung the mirror in
her private bathroom.

319
00:28:43.426 --> 00:28:46.901
Two weeks later. her niece Beatrice
finds Mary dead in the bathtub.

320
00:28:46.902 --> 00:28:50.738
Now. the official coroner's report lists
the cause of death as. get this...

321
00:28:50.739 --> 00:28:52.936
dehydration.

322
00:28:52.937 --> 00:28:56.452
The woman died of thirst while soaking
in a full tub for three days.

323
00:28:56.453 --> 00:29:01.008
The next case of note is Alice Carden
in Lake Geneva. Wisconsin. 1943.

324
00:29:01.009 --> 00:29:04.125
Neighbors reported hearing screams
and loud bangs from the house.

325
00:29:04.125 --> 00:29:07.162
The police found the children
drowned in a locked cistern.

326
00:29:07.163 --> 00:29:08.760
Alice herself was in the nursery.

327
00:29:08.761 --> 00:29:10.478
and both of her legs are
completely shattered.

328
00:29:10.479 --> 00:29:13.955
Her left arm is broken in four places.
and 6 of her ribs are crushed.

329
00:29:13.956 --> 00:29:17.631
In her right hand is a large hammer she's
been using to break her own bones.

330
00:29:17.632 --> 00:29:20.349
They find her just as she's
going to work on her skull.

331
00:29:20.350 --> 00:29:22.586
Her right arm. though.
is completely unharmed.

332
00:29:22.587 --> 00:29:26.542
Because she needed it.
To wield the hammer.

333
00:29:26.543 --> 00:29:29.260
Alice later says she believed she was
tucking the children into their beds

334
00:29:29.261 --> 00:29:30.698
as she sealed them
into the cistern.

335
00:29:30.699 --> 00:29:32.057
She never recovers
from her injuries.

336
00:29:32.058 --> 00:29:34.135
And. oh. the family kept
several dogs at the farm.

337
00:29:34.136 --> 00:29:37.212
including an Australian
shepherd for the children.

338
00:29:49.361 --> 00:29:50.990
Let's eat.

339
00:29:55.675 --> 00:29:58.862
Who exactly are you talking to?
On those tapes?

340
00:30:02.348 --> 00:30:05.664
All the people who stared. pointed.

341
00:30:05.665 --> 00:30:08.541
The kids at school who
always found out.

342
00:30:08.542 --> 00:30:12.127
I guess I'm talking to everyone
who ever called Dad a murderer.

343
00:30:12.818 --> 00:30:14.845
Called you a murderer.

344
00:30:15.615 --> 00:30:19.051
Look. Kaylie. we were just kids.

345
00:30:19.052 --> 00:30:21.848
We made up a scary story so we
wouldn't have to accept the fact

346
00:30:21.849 --> 00:30:24.166
that our father was
a murderer. He was.

347
00:30:24.167 --> 00:30:26.626
He was a sick man who
tortured and killed our...

348
00:30:34.716 --> 00:30:37.664
You can call me crazy all you like.

349
00:30:38.752 --> 00:30:41.655
But you're not allowed to
talk about him that way.

350
00:30:44.427 --> 00:30:47.982
Tobin Capp. 1955. Starved to
death in his own bedroom.

351
00:30:47.983 --> 00:30:51.059
The mirror was hung over his dresser.
He had a pet Dalmatian.

352
00:30:51.060 --> 00:30:52.937
1965. California.

353
00:30:52.938 --> 00:30:55.934
The mirror hangs in the lobby of
the Hill Trust Bank in San Diego.

354
00:30:55.935 --> 00:30:59.091
A 10-year teller. Marcia Wicker.
locks her manager in the bank vault

355
00:30:59.092 --> 00:31:01.809
and then chews through
a live power line.

356
00:31:01.810 --> 00:31:04.486
- 1975. Marisol Chavez...
- Kaylie...

357
00:31:04.487 --> 00:31:07.403
dies in her bedroom of
hemorrhaging due to a miscarriage.

358
00:31:07.404 --> 00:31:09.441
In her nightstand. they find
every single one of her teeth

359
00:31:09.442 --> 00:31:11.839
in a little plastic bag and
a pair of bloody pliers.

360
00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:13.597
- 2002...
- There's a huge difference

361
00:31:13.598 --> 00:31:15.235
between causation and correlation.

362
00:31:15.236 --> 00:31:16.594
I know the difference. thank you.

363
00:31:16.595 --> 00:31:19.511
OK then. In 2001. Mom and
Dad bought that new couch.

364
00:31:19.512 --> 00:31:22.828
Same year. Grandpa had a heart attack.
Robbie Schultz got hit by a car.

365
00:31:22.829 --> 00:31:24.786
And our cat ran away.

366
00:31:24.787 --> 00:31:27.264
How much of that do you
blame on that couch?

367
00:31:27.265 --> 00:31:29.182
Can I get back to this now?

368
00:31:29.183 --> 00:31:31.539
Sure. but let's get to it. Kaylie.

369
00:31:31.540 --> 00:31:34.125
Let's talk about why
we're really here.

370
00:31:35.177 --> 00:31:36.681
Let's.

371
00:31:37.534 --> 00:31:39.771
2002.

372
00:31:39.772 --> 00:31:43.278
The Lasser Glass adorns the
home office of Alan Russell.

373
00:31:43.968 --> 00:31:47.348
Software designer.
Husband to Marie.

374
00:31:48.124 --> 00:31:49.921
Father to Timothy and Kaylie.

375
00:31:49.922 --> 00:31:51.400
Within 2 weeks of its arrival.

376
00:31:51.401 --> 00:31:53.438
Marie suffers an intense
psychological breakdown

377
00:31:53.439 --> 00:31:56.515
and is tortured and murdered
in the family home.

378
00:31:56.516 --> 00:31:58.304
By whom?

379
00:31:58.993 --> 00:32:01.020
By her husband.

380
00:32:01.990 --> 00:32:03.588
So say the police reports.

381
00:32:03.589 --> 00:32:07.492
And her husband was shot
to death by her own son.

382
00:32:08.664 --> 00:32:10.964
Right in front of her daughter.

383
00:32:14.019 --> 00:32:16.535
I intend to prove that none of
the people I've just described

384
00:32:16.536 --> 00:32:18.893
were responsible for their actions.

385
00:32:18.894 --> 00:32:22.010
Alan Russell was not a
murderer. He was a victim.

386
00:32:22.011 --> 00:32:23.528
One of many. as it turns out.

387
00:32:23.529 --> 00:32:26.166
Victims of the supernatural force
that resides in that mirror.

388
00:32:26.167 --> 00:32:29.910
So why don't we just end it right
now and smash the goddamn thing?

389
00:32:31.481 --> 00:32:33.747
You really don't remember. do you?

390
00:32:37.475 --> 00:32:39.855
Remember what?

391
00:32:40.552 --> 00:32:43.932
Please. smash it. by all means.

392
00:32:48.385 --> 00:32:49.764
Okay.

393
00:33:04.449 --> 00:33:08.124
You know. I've learned a lot about what
happens to people when they can't...

394
00:33:08.125 --> 00:33:10.664
can't process something horrible.

395
00:33:12.321 --> 00:33:16.064
The mind creates all kinds of
protections to help them cope.

396
00:33:17.316 --> 00:33:19.273
And once that belief's taken root.

397
00:33:19.274 --> 00:33:23.575
the mind takes random information and
forces it to support that narrative.

398
00:33:26.667 --> 00:33:29.223
How many thousands of records
did you have to pore through

399
00:33:29.224 --> 00:33:31.741
to find 12 or 13 that
support your case?

400
00:33:31.742 --> 00:33:34.485
Why did you put the stool down?

401
00:33:40.174 --> 00:33:42.570
Because I'm trying to have
a conversation with you.

402
00:33:42.571 --> 00:33:45.767
Uh-huh. Only one person I
know of was ever documented

403
00:33:45.768 --> 00:33:49.364
trying to break the mirror.
Oliver Jeffries. 1971.

404
00:33:49.365 --> 00:33:51.282
A teacher at Manhattan's
Duhame Academy.

405
00:33:51.283 --> 00:33:52.840
where the mirror hung in
the central lecture hall.

406
00:33:52.841 --> 00:33:55.478
One morning he reportedly ran at
the mirror with a fireplace poker.

407
00:33:55.479 --> 00:33:57.156
shouting about how it
needed to be destroyed.

408
00:33:57.157 --> 00:33:59.594
but he never struck a blow.
According to the students.

409
00:33:59.595 --> 00:34:01.152
he stood there quietly
for almost a minute

410
00:34:01.153 --> 00:34:04.294
before walking out of the
hall and into traffic.

411
00:34:05.469 --> 00:34:07.865
It's clearly capable of
defending itself. and...

412
00:34:07.866 --> 00:34:10.451
...I think it just disarmed you.

413
00:34:13.501 --> 00:34:16.057
You know why I didn't
smash the mirror. Kaylie?

414
00:34:16.058 --> 00:34:20.882
Besides you getting fired or charged
with destruction of property?

415
00:34:21.573 --> 00:34:23.714
It isn't mine to break.

416
00:34:24.490 --> 00:34:27.047
No one can break your
delusion for you.

417
00:34:27.048 --> 00:34:29.125
You have to do it yourself.

418
00:34:29.126 --> 00:34:31.744
Which leads me to my
final precaution.

419
00:34:32.802 --> 00:34:35.278
You're looking at a
20-pound Danforth anchor.

420
00:34:35.279 --> 00:34:38.555
Another 20 pounds added with barbells.
attached to a modified ballast rail

421
00:34:38.556 --> 00:34:41.153
and a spring pin lock connected
to a mechanical kitchen timer.

422
00:34:41.154 --> 00:34:44.509
No electricity. which is important.
and we're about ten seconds away.

423
00:34:44.510 --> 00:34:46.827
If the timer is not manually
reset every 30 minutes.

424
00:34:46.828 --> 00:34:49.425
that is. if no one is
here to stop it...

425
00:34:54.381 --> 00:34:57.776
The mirror goes right there. And
the only thing to prevent that

426
00:34:57.777 --> 00:35:01.053
from happening again is
our continued survival.

427
00:35:01.054 --> 00:35:03.571
You know why we don't have to
wait for it to come out and play?

428
00:35:03.572 --> 00:35:06.528
Because we've got a
loaded gun to its head.

429
00:35:06.529 --> 00:35:09.636
And I expect it'll be
eager to defend itself.

430
00:36:35.042 --> 00:36:36.466
Aah!

431
00:36:50.306 --> 00:36:52.823
It doesn't hurt. It doesn't hurt.

432
00:36:52.824 --> 00:36:56.125
It doesn't hurt. It doesn't hurt.

433
00:37:22.795 --> 00:37:25.901
Hey guys?

434
00:37:27.310 --> 00:37:29.849
Come into my office for a second.

435
00:37:31.626 --> 00:37:36.140
I thought I was pretty clear about
you guys not messing around in here.

436
00:37:36.141 --> 00:37:37.726
We don't.

437
00:37:38.419 --> 00:37:40.321
I don't like it in here.

438
00:37:41.017 --> 00:37:43.794
All right. well. what is this?

439
00:37:47.490 --> 00:37:49.233
We didn't do that.

440
00:37:50.048 --> 00:37:51.845
OK.

441
00:37:51.846 --> 00:37:56.680
You know. I can hear you guys at
night. messing around in here.

442
00:37:56.681 --> 00:38:01.156
I was a kid once. too. I get it.
I know the move has been difficult.

443
00:38:01.157 --> 00:38:03.354
This isn't gonna happen anymore.

444
00:38:03.355 --> 00:38:05.671
OK?

445
00:38:05.672 --> 00:38:08.389
And if you're messing around
with your mother's plants.

446
00:38:08.390 --> 00:38:10.452
you're gonna cut that out. too.

447
00:38:14.424 --> 00:38:17.340
You know what dead
plants are evidence of to me?

448
00:38:17.341 --> 00:38:20.482
Problems with the water
supply and maybe a bad tank.

449
00:38:21.657 --> 00:38:24.852
I seem to remember drinking
out of a Brita filter.

450
00:38:24.853 --> 00:38:27.050
Oliver Jeffries. dead
plants in the classroom.

451
00:38:27.051 --> 00:38:29.088
Tobin Capp. dead
plants in the bedroom.

452
00:38:29.089 --> 00:38:31.686
Garden service at Hill Trust
Bank couldn't understand

453
00:38:31.687 --> 00:38:34.843
why they had dead plants
all over the place.

454
00:38:34.844 --> 00:38:36.481
Live plant.

455
00:38:36.482 --> 00:38:40.077
Live plants in the living room.

456
00:38:40.078 --> 00:38:43.594
Live plants. plants that have life.

457
00:38:43.595 --> 00:38:45.232
- These are your rules. by the way.
- Give it time.

458
00:38:45.233 --> 00:38:47.230
It always starts with
the low-hanging fruit.

459
00:38:47.231 --> 00:38:49.428
It wasn't just the plants
it fed on. though.

460
00:38:49.429 --> 00:38:51.546
There was another variable. too.

461
00:38:51.547 --> 00:38:54.245
Dog!

462
00:38:57.341 --> 00:38:59.298
Sorry. Dog.

463
00:39:06.133 --> 00:39:07.796
Hydrate.

464
00:39:18.041 --> 00:39:20.637
- Come on. boy.
- Come on. Mason. Go fetch.

465
00:39:20.638 --> 00:39:22.995
- Come on. Mason.
- Go fetch.

466
00:39:22.996 --> 00:39:25.673
Chase the stick. Chase the stick.

467
00:39:25.674 --> 00:39:27.576
Come on. Go. Go.

468
00:39:29.430 --> 00:39:31.307
I mean. the whole
reason I got this thing

469
00:39:31.308 --> 00:39:33.665
was because you were freaked
out that we weren't safe.

470
00:39:33.666 --> 00:39:35.303
Said you saw somebody down here.

471
00:39:35.304 --> 00:39:37.581
Yeah. but that doesn't
make me feel safer.

472
00:39:37.582 --> 00:39:40.658
Quite the opposite. actually.

473
00:39:40.659 --> 00:39:44.334
OK. I will lock it up. unloaded.

474
00:39:44.335 --> 00:39:48.522
where I'm sure it'll come in very
handy in the case of an emergency.

475
00:39:51.688 --> 00:39:54.034
Grotesque cow.

476
00:40:01.199 --> 00:40:03.578
What did you just say to me?

477
00:40:04.675 --> 00:40:06.657
I didn't say anything.

478
00:40:40.720 --> 00:40:44.145
Ow! Jesus!

479
00:40:46.953 --> 00:40:48.391
Alan!

480
00:40:48.392 --> 00:40:50.818
I'm working!

481
00:41:03.777 --> 00:41:05.804
Who are you talking to?

482
00:41:11.609 --> 00:41:14.069
Were you gonna do something
about the damn barking?

483
00:41:16.205 --> 00:41:18.961
There's something wrong with
the dog. Alan. He bit me.

484
00:41:18.962 --> 00:41:21.388
Are you OK?

485
00:41:22.159 --> 00:41:24.221
I'm fine.

486
00:41:27.114 --> 00:41:30.629
You know. you are just lost
in your own world in here.

487
00:41:30.630 --> 00:41:33.347
I'm not lost in my own
world! I'm working!

488
00:41:33.348 --> 00:41:34.825
I know that.

489
00:41:34.826 --> 00:41:38.062
I've supported that.
This isn't you working hard.

490
00:41:38.063 --> 00:41:41.379
When you start your own
business. it's all on you.

491
00:41:41.380 --> 00:41:44.123
- I know that. Alan!
- I have to do this!

492
00:41:46.815 --> 00:41:50.730
Guys. Listen. you got to
do me a special favor today.

493
00:41:50.731 --> 00:41:52.728
I have a golf session
with a client.

494
00:41:52.729 --> 00:41:56.324
And I'm gonna need you to
stay out of my office. OK?

495
